					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">blargg wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">The point is that you use a fast, cheap microcontroller in place of an FPGA to reduce cost, nothing more. It's just to provide simple functions like scanline IRQ or bank switching, not extra processing. And then we'd come up with an easy-to-use design so that every homebrew developer could use the same mapper, not make a bunch of custom mappers as Bregalad thought I meant.</div>
<br />You mean agree on a final mapper that would have enough features for everyone and then stick on it ? The MMC5 has almost all features one can think of, while being able to simulate lower features of lower mapper at almost perfection, would it be the universal mapper you're talking about ?
<br />
<br />A MCU based mapper running with a PLL clock should definitely check for another thing at start-up to snch with the CPU (such as a simple rising edge of M2 or something in that sense). Then the mapper would have something like 32 cycles for each CPU cycle, maybe it's just enough to check if the mapper is written to and then react more or less immediately to it (some delay cycles woudldn't mapper when it comes to bankswitching). The problem is that mirroring control and CHR bankswitching should by synched with the PPU, wich is much faster than the CPU.</div>

